      CDS
   =20
 =20
Loosely speaking, a credit default swap is an insurance policy on the bonds=
 of a country or company. If you buy a $100 bond and a $100 CDS, you should=
 always get back $100: If the bond defaults and pays back only $30, the CDS=
 should pay you $70; if it defaults and pays $0, the CDS should pay you $10=
0. (If the bond pays back at par, the CDS should pay you zero.)One way to t=
hink about the mechanics is that, if there is a default on the bond, you ha=
nd the bond over to the CDS seller, and the CDS seller gives you $100. That=
 way you get your $100, and the CDS seller gets whatever the bond is worth,=
 $30 or $0 or conceivably even $100 or more. (It is possible to have a defa=
ult that triggers CDS but that leaves the value of the bond fairly intact.)=
 This is not quite the actual mechanics =E2=80=94=C2=A0the actual mechanics=
  involve an auction for the defaulted bonds to set a cash settlement price=
, which can lead to strange results =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is roughly the ri=
ght way to think about it.If you do think about it this way you can imagine=
 ways for it to go wrong. One way for it to go wrong is: Imagine a sanction=
s regime that banned anyone from owning, trading or transferring Russian bo=
nds. If you owned a Russian bond that defaulted and was worthless, and you =
owned CDS, you=E2=80=99d call up your CDS counterparty and say =E2=80=9Chey=
 I=E2=80=99m going to hand you this bond in exchange for $100=E2=80=9D and =
the counterparty would say =E2=80=9Cno you won=E2=80=99t, you can=E2=80=99t=
, those bonds are not transferable.=E2=80=9D And the CDS would (maybe?) not=
 pay out. This seems absurd, but as we  discussed last week, there is some =
risk of some form of it happening to Russian sovereign bonds: There are eno=
ugh restrictions on transfer that it might be hard to deliver bonds to sett=
le CDS, which might result in CDS not paying out much.Another way for it to=
 go wrong is: Imagine if, instead of just defaulting on the bonds, Russia s=
ent thieves to sneak into your vault and steal all the bonds. You=E2=80=99d=
 wake up with no bonds. You=E2=80=99d call your CDS counterparty and say =
=E2=80=9CI have a $100 loss on my bonds, please reimburse me,=E2=80=9D and =
the counterparty would say =E2=80=9Cokay hand over the bonds=E2=80=9D and y=
ou=E2=80=99d say =E2=80=9CI can=E2=80=99t, they=E2=80=99re gone,=E2=80=9D a=
nd the CDS would not pay out.That one seems even more absurd, but you can g=
et weirdly close to it. The problem with CDS is that the contracts do not r=
eference specific bonds, but rather refer to categories of =E2=80=9Cdeliver=
able=E2=80=9D bonds. A CDS contract might cover, for instance, dollar-denom=
inated bonds of a Russian issuer. If Russia changes the characteristics of =
a bond in certain ways, the bond stops being deliverable, so you can=E2=80=
=99t deliver it to a CDS seller, so you can=E2=80=99t get a payout.[3]  Thi=
s is bizarre:Russia and Russian companies will be allowed to pay foreign cr=
editors in rubles, according to a decree signed by President Vladimir Putin=
 on Saturday, as a way to stave off defaults while capital controls remain =
in place. =C2=A0The decree establishes temporary rules for sovereign and co=
rporate debtors to make payments to creditors from =E2=80=9Ccountries that =
engage in hostile activities=E2=80=9D against Russia, its companies and cit=
izens. The government will prepare a list of such countries within two days=
. ...While some of Russia=E2=80=99s foreign sovereign bonds allow payments =
in rubles, the new measure could still pose a=C2=A0problem=C2=A0for holders=
 of credit-default swaps, which are used as insurance in case of a default.=
=C2=A0That=E2=80=99s because, given the capital controls in Russia and the =
sanctions, the payment in rubles =E2=80=9Cmay render these bonds out of sco=
pe for CDS as =E2=80=98obligations=E2=80=99 and =E2=80=98deliverable obliga=
tions=E2=80=99,=E2=80=9D JPMorgan Chase & Co. strategists led by Trang Nguy=
en wrote in a note to investors on Friday.=C2=A0If a bond issuer defaults s=
o hard that it renders your bonds undeliverable, then that=E2=80=99s when y=
ou most need CDS to pay off!
