      2-and-20
   =20
 =20
If you invest in a venture capital fund that has a 10-year life and a 2% an=
nual management fee and a 20% performance fee, in expectation you will pay =
about 20% of your investment to the manager in management fees. (Plus, you =
hope, and the manager hopes, even more in performance fees.) I suppose they=
 could =E2=80=A6=C2=A0just =E2=80=A6=C2=A0take the 20% up front?The Securit=
ies and Exchange Commission [Friday]=C2=A0charged venture capital fund advi=
ser Alumni Ventures Group, LLC (AVG) with making misleading statements abou=
t its management fees and engaging in inter-fund transactions in breach of =
fund operating agreements. =E2=80=A6According to the SEC=E2=80=99s order, A=
VG=E2=80=99s website and other marketing communications represented that it=
s management fee for the venture capital funds that it managed was the =E2=
=80=9Cindustry standard =E2=80=982 and 20.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D The order foun=
d that these representations were misleading because they led some investor=
s to believe that AVG would collect a two-percent management fee during eac=
h year of its funds=E2=80=99 10-year term, and separately collect a 20-perc=
ent performance fee. According to the order, AVG=E2=80=99s typical practice=
 was instead to assess management fees totaling 20 percent of an investor=
=E2=80=99s fund investment (representing ten years=E2=80=99 of two-percent =
annual management fees) upon the investor=E2=80=99s initial fund investment=
.Honestly that is a weird move? From the SEC complaint:In reality, AVG=E2=
=80=99s practice was to assess the entire 20 percent in management fees=E2=
=80=94i.e., 10 years=E2=80=99 worth of management fees of two percent per a=
nnum=E2=80=94upfront at the time an investor made the capital contribution.=
 For example, if an investor contributed $100,000 to a Fund managed by AVG,=
 AVG would immediately assess 20 percent, or $20,000, as its management fee=
 for the expected life of the Fund. AVG typically drew and spent most or al=
l of this $20,000 to pay expenses during the first year of the Fund=E2=80=
=99s operations. ...AVG=E2=80=99s accelerated collection of its annual mana=
gement fee amounted to an interest-free loan from the Funds that it managed=
. If the Funds had charged AVG a reasonable rate of interest on the advance=
d fees, AVG would have paid the Funds $4,791,401.I feel like the point of t=
he 2% management fee is to sort of keep the lights on during the life of th=
e fund. If you spend it all in the first year, how do you keep the lights o=
n for the other nine years?=C2=A0
