d-color: #ccc;"> the big ESG issue</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">=E2=80=9CUkraine is one of the most important ESG issues we=E2=80=
=99ve ever had,=E2=80=9D said Philippe Zaouati, chief executive of Mirova, =
the $30 billion sustainable-investing unit affiliated with Natixis Investme=
nt Managers. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a vital issue for energy and human right=
s, and questions whether we still want to live in a democracy or not.=E2=80=
=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One point here is that, wh=
ile this is an ESG issue,=C2=A0it is not one that implicates only or primar=
ily=C2=A0<em>ESG investors</em>. Every company and investor faces some pres=
sure to have a position on Russia. Some level of public morality, and some =
accounting for systemic risks, is now built into every aspect of internatio=
nal finance.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The two theories of ESG each h=
ave odd implications. The risk/sustainability theory essentially <em>antici=
pates=C2=A0</em>government actions: You get out of a business because you t=
hink that, in the long term, future regulation will make it untenable. Some=
times this puts investors in conflict with the actual goals of current regu=
lators. For instance, many ESG investors avoid fossil fuels out of an expec=
tation that future regulations will ban them, but in the U.S. actual Republ=
ican governments tend to want more fossil fuels; I <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26940247.278607/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMDUvdGhlLWJvYXJkLWNhbi10LWZpcmUte=
W91LWlmLWl0LXF1aXRzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMDcyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1h=
aWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDMwNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9=
uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0310f997" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">wrote last year</a> =
about anti-ESG rules in Texas:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
Not only has Texas not taken steps to limit oil and gas drilling, it has ta=
ken steps to make it illegal=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>to support oil and gas =
drilling. If your theory of ESG investing is =E2=80=9Cwe have to divest fro=
m fossil fuels because ultimately regulators will ban them,=E2=80=9D it has=
 to feel a little weird when the regulators instead=C2=A0<em>ban divesting =
from fossil fuels.</em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Simila=
rly, there has been a great deal of =E2=80=9Cself-sanctioning=E2=80=9D of R=
ussian oil exports in anticipation of future broader sanctions, even though=
 actual sanctions so far have not only exempted=C2=A0oil and gas but, as of=
 last week, specifically encouraged=C2=A0the continued financing of Russian=
 energy exports. From the U.S. Department of the Treasury=E2=80=99s <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26940247.278607/aHR0cHM6L=
y9ob21lLnRyZWFzdXJ5Lmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2VzL2p5MDYyNA/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB128a599f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">Office of Foreign Assets Control last week</a=
>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Treasury remains committed t=
o permitting energy-related payments =E2=80=94 ranging from production to c=
onsumption for a wide array of energy sources =E2=80=94 involving specified=
 sanctioned Russian banks. To help protect Americans, partners, and allies =
from higher energy prices that would drive more resources to Russia, Treasu=
ry swiftly issued and updated Russia-related guidance to allow U.S. financi=
al institutions to continue processing these transactions and underscore th=
at such activity is not prohibited by sanctions. While current circumstance=
s and the dangers from Russia=E2=80=99s war in Ukraine may lead entities an=
d individuals to make their own risk assessments and business decisions, Tr=
easury is making clear that sanctions will not block energy payments.</p></=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">OFAC is constrained by U.S. politic=
s, and U.S. politicians do not particularly want to see energy price inflat=
ion, so they exempted Russian oil from sanctions and then made a point of c=
larifying that so no one was confused into self-sanctioning. People self-sa=
nctioned anyway. And they were =E2=80=A6=C2=A0possibly right? <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26940247.278607/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMDYvYnJlbnQtb2lsLXNvYXJzLW=
Fib3ZlLTEzNS1vbi1mZWFycy1vdmVyLXRpZ2h0ZW5pbmctbWFya2V0P2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMDcyM=
l9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90=
