<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">CDS</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Loosely speaking, a credit default swa=
p is an insurance policy on the bonds of a country or company. If you buy a=
 $100 bond and a $100 CDS, you should always get back $100: If the bond def=
aults and pays back only $30, the CDS should pay you $70; if it defaults an=
d pays $0, the CDS should pay you $100. (If the bond pays back at par, the =
CDS should pay you zero.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way to think =
about the mechanics is that, if there is a default on the bond, you hand th=
e bond over to the CDS seller, and the CDS seller gives you $100. That way =
you get your $100, and the CDS seller gets whatever the bond is worth, $30 =
or $0 or conceivably even $100 or more. (It is possible to have a default t=
hat triggers CDS but that leaves the value of the bond fairly intact.) This=
 is not quite the actual mechanics =E2=80=94=C2=A0the actual mechanics <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26940247.278607/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMTEtMTIvc2VhcnMtZ=
m91bmQtc29tZS11c2VmdWwtYm9uZHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMwNzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21l=
ZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMzA3JnV0bV9jYW1=
wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8457e721" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> involve a=
n auction</a> for the defaulted bonds to set a cash settlement price, which=
 can lead to strange results =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is roughly the right way=
 to think about it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you do think about i=
t this way you can imagine ways for it to go wrong. One way for it to go wr=
ong is: Imagine a sanctions regime that banned anyone from owning, trading =
or transferring Russian bonds. If you owned a Russian bond that defaulted a=
nd was worthless, and you owned CDS, you=E2=80=99d call up your CDS counter=
party and say =E2=80=9Chey I=E2=80=99m going to hand you this bond in excha=
nge for $100=E2=80=9D and the counterparty would say =E2=80=9Cno you won=E2=
=80=99t, you can=E2=80=99t, those bonds are not transferable.=E2=80=9D And =
the CDS would (maybe?) not pay out. This seems absurd, but as we <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26940247.278607/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMDMvdW5pbnZlc3RhYmx=
lLW1hcmtldHMtYXJlLWhhcmQtdG8tdHJhZGU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMwNzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdX=
RtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMzA3JnV0b=
V9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB99eaacf8" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> dis=
cussed last week</a>, there is some risk of some form of it happening to Ru=
ssian sovereign bonds: There are enough restrictions on transfer that it mi=
ght be hard to deliver bonds to settle CDS, which might result in CDS not p=
aying out much.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another way for it to go wr=
ong is: Imagine if, instead of just defaulting on the bonds, Russia sent th=
ieves to sneak into your vault and steal all the bonds. You=E2=80=99d wake =
up with no bonds. You=E2=80=99d call your CDS counterparty and say =E2=80=
=9CI have a $100 loss on my bonds, please reimburse me,=E2=80=9D and the co=
unterparty would say =E2=80=9Cokay hand over the bonds=E2=80=9D and you=E2=
=80=99d say =E2=80=9CI can=E2=80=99t, they=E2=80=99re gone,=E2=80=9D and th=
e CDS would not pay out.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That one seems eve=
n more absurd, but you can get weirdly close to it. The problem with CDS is=
 that the contracts do not reference specific bonds, but rather refer to ca=
tegories of =E2=80=9Cdeliverable=E2=80=9D bonds. A CDS contract might cover=
, for instance, dollar-denominated bonds of a Russian issuer. If Russia cha=
nges the characteristics of a bond in certain ways, the bond stops being de=
liverable, so you can=E2=80=99t deliver it to a CDS seller, so you can=E2=
=80=99t get a payout.[3] <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/26940247.278607/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVz=
LzIwMjItMDMtMDUvcHV0aW4tc2Vla3MtdG8tYXZlcnQtZGVmYXVsdHMtd2l0aC1ydWJsZS1wYXl=
tZW50cy10by1jcmVkaXRvcnM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMwNzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT=
1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMzA3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnb=
j1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf2bdb1d3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> This is bizarre=
</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Russia and Russian compan=
ies will be allowed to pay foreign creditors in rubles, according to a decr=
ee signed by President Vladimir Putin on Saturday, as a way to stave off de=
faults while capital controls remain in place. =C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">The decree establishes temporary rules for sovereign and corpora=
te debtors to make payments to creditors from =E2=80=9Ccountries that engag=
e in hostile activities=E2=80=9D against Russia, its companies and citizens=
. The government will prepare a list of such countries within two days. ...=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While some of Russia=E2=80=99s foreign sov=
ereign bonds allow payments in rubles, the new measure could still pose a=
=C2=A0problem=C2=A0for holders of credit-default swaps, which are used as i=
nsurance in case of a default.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=
=E2=80=99s because, given the capital controls in Russia and the sanctions,=
 the payment in rubles =E2=80=9Cmay render these bonds out of scope for CDS=
 as =E2=80=98obligations=E2=80=99 and =E2=80=98deliverable obligations=E2=
=80=99,=E2=80=9D JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. strategists led by Trang Nguyen w=
rote in a note to investors on Friday.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">If a bond issuer defaults so hard that it renders your bonds=
 undeliverable, then that=E2=80=99s when you most need CDS to pay off!</p><=
